Answer.feedback: I encountered 2 issues. First, a minor issue, but in the second example listed under "3D Bar Charts: Volume." You say there that "groups 'A' and 'B' have an outcome of only 1 for proposal one while 'C' still has an outcome of 100", different from the previous chart where all three groups had a value of 100 and proposal one was shown as a cube. But you can clear see from the chart that it is group A that still has a value of 100. Either the text is wrong or the chart is wrong.The 2nd issue I encountered is a bit worse, and that is that frankly the explanation for how the 3D charts handle proportion differences in the groups is very unclear. In 3D-4 I am first given an example of this, and the hint just outright says it's hard to tell from 3D charts alone and I should read the text. Okay, fair enough.But then in 3D-5 and told to "notice how the sizes of the 3D bars change based on the change in proportion of the groups." But I'm given no explanation as to how or why. Yes, if I scroll up I can see a difference, but I am left wondering why even.Then in the next section "3D Bar Charts: Different Sized Groups" I get an explanation that it's represented by scaling the axes, which I can sort of see from comparing the two charts, but it's not clear how one tells the difference from scaling axes due to different proportions and different outcomes for different groups.Overall I am left with impression that the 3D charts are extremely terrible at representing the data when the groups are different proportions to each other. Maybe that's just a weakness of the charts, but if it's not the case then there is probably an issue either with the explanation or my understanding, or perhaps both.

Answer.feedback: What was unclear? *All* of the 3D graphs. I did try to move them around, and they did move, but I didn't know what I was looking at, I didn't know why they had to be 3D, and really, without numbers I didn't know how to interpret them. I answered 3D-1 only because there was information in the description, so I used that. The others made no sense to me at all so I just picked "none." Multiple choice questions I don't know how to answer can be a problem because I could accidentally pick the right answer and give the impression I understand when I don't. If there had been an "I don't know" answer choice I would have picked that. There wasn't so I went with "none" in the hope that it would always be incorrect and therefore show that I didn't understand the information. (Note: My experience with bar graphs is several decades old and I have no experience with 3D graphs of any type; in fact, this is the first time I've even seen them. Maybe there's a learning curve when it comes to visualizing data that way.)
